President Biden has spoken with the family of Evan Gershkovich, the Wall Street Journal reporter who was wrongfully detained by Russia. The President expressed his commitment to securing Evan's release, as well as that of Paul Whelan, who is also wrongfully detained in Russia. The charges against Evan are baseless, and the State Department continues to seek consular access to him.

In other news, the Biden administration has unveiled a stronger approach to disrupting the trafficking of illicit fentanyl into the United States. This includes coordinating federal actions with international partners, strengthening coordination between U.S. intelligence and domestic law enforcement, working with the private sector to protect the U.S. financial system, and calling on Congress to close legal loopholes for illicit synthetic drugs. The administration is also expanding access to opioid overdose reversal products and launching a national campaign to educate young people on the dangers of fentanyl.

Additionally, President Biden released a statement commemorating the 55th anniversary of the Fair Housing Act, emphasizing the need for a fair housing market and acknowledging the work that still needs to be done to address segregation, disparities in homeownership, and the racial wealth gap.

During the flight to Belfast, the President also made phone calls and engaged with his team on various matters. However, there will not be a press conference on this trip. The President's family members traveling with him include his sister, Valerie Biden Owens, and his son, Hunter Biden. The President's plans for re-election have not changed, and he intends to run, although he has not made a formal announcement yet.